{
  "text": "The initial bile flow rate (220 l/10 min) and BA output rate (2.8 mol/10 min) in the rats in the current study are in good agreement with those measured in other studies [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] in fasted adult biliary fistula rats. For 250-g rats, Higgins et al. [CITATION_3] found bile flow to be 180 l/10 min and BA output to be 2.7 mol/10 min. Dumaswala et al. [CITATION_4] found bile flow to be 196 l/10 min and BA output to be 2 mol/10 min. Because the total BA pool for a 250-g rat is ϳ50-60 mol (41), the fistula rats in the current study excreted Х30% of their BA pool per hour. Therefore, it is not surprising that infusing donor bile into the intestine was necessary to obtain a response to NT. The BA pool was so easily depleted that BA output fell 40-50% over 2-3 h, even when donor bile was infused at the excretion rate. Despite our difficulty in mimicking an intact EHC in the rat fistula model, NT infusion in rats receiving donor bile maintained a 10-20% higher BA output relative to controls for Ͼ2 h. The fact that NT enhanced BA output only when sufficient bile was present in the intestine suggested that the effect of NT was on the rate of intestinal BA uptake. This was proven by showing that NT increased [ 3 H]TC uptake from the intestine but not from blood.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "41703952",
    "[CITATION_2]": "5863566",
